\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs24 \cf0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 It's the 
\f1\b tailored Expanding Photosphere Method
\f0\b0  result from Vogl et al. 2025, the only entry on the H0DN figure that's truly distance-ladder-free end-to-end, using NLTE radiative transfer modeling of Type II supernovae to derive geometric distances per SN with no calibrator galaxies. We've also worked through SNe II EPM in physical detail, and through the broader landscape of every other method on the figure. Now I can give you the deeper picture: what makes adh0cc structurally unique among H
\f2 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  measurements, why its emergence over the past few years has shifted the H
\f2 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  tension landscape meaningfully, and how it should enter your fluid-vs-axion EDE inference.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 What "adh0cc" means as a name\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 The name is a play on the LaTeX-style embedding of $H_0$ in "ad hoc" \'97 i.e., the symbol $H_0$ literally appears in the label "adh0cc". In the Vogl group's framing, the "ad hoc" part is gentle self-deprecation about the method: each SN II is fit individually with custom radiative transfer models, with no shared calibration, no global ladder, no anchor \'97 every distance is computed 
\f3\i ad hoc
\f0\i0  from the SN's own spectra and photometry.\
The name also nods to a deeper philosophical point about the method. Most H
\f2 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  measurements operate by anchoring everything to a few well-studied calibrators and propagating distances outward. adh0cc goes the other direction: there's no anchor, every SN is its own anchor, and the H
\f2 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  measurement is the statistical average over many independent geometric distances.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

