\ls4\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Treats SNe II as standardizable candles via the plateau-luminosity / expansion-velocity / color correlation\
\ls4\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Calibrators are SNe II in Cepheid/TRGB-distance hosts\
\ls4\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Hubble diagram is constructed in the standard way\
\ls4\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Per-SN distance precision: ~10\'9615%\
\ls4\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 H
\f2 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  \uc0\u8776  75.4 \'b1 3.8\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 adh0cc (tailored EPM, Vogl+25):
\f0\b0 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls5\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Treats each SN II geometrically via radiative transfer\
\ls5\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 No calibrator galaxies; no shared anchor\
\ls5\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Each SN provides its own distance independently\
\ls5\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Per-SN distance precision: ~5%\
\ls5\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 H
\f2 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  \uc0\u8776  75 \'b1 2\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Both methods use the same physical objects (SNe II), but:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls6\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 SCM is a 
\f3\i empirical standard candle
\f0\i0  method requiring external calibration\
\ls6\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 EPM is a 
\f3\i first-principles geometric
\f0\i0  method requiring no external calibration\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 The fact that they give consistent H
\f2 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  values (~75) by completely different routes is itself a useful internal check. It demonstrates that SNe II as a population aren't uniformly biased in either method \'97 if SCM-calibrated H
\f2 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  is wrong, it's wrong differently than tailored-EPM H
\f2 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  is wrong.\
For your EDE work, both methods enter the H0DN network independently, and both pull H
\f2 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  toward the high side.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 The future of adh0cc\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Worth being concrete about how the method scales:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 JWST-enabled extension to higher redshift.
\f0\b0  SN II spectroscopy at z > 0.1 has been hard from the ground because the relevant wavelength range shifts into the IR. JWST NIRSpec opens this up. Within the next 2\'963 years, expect tailored EPM samples extending to z ~ 0.2, providing a cleaner Hubble diagram with reduced PV systematic.\

\f1\b Larger samples from current and upcoming surveys.
\f0\b0  ZTF, ATLAS, BlackGEM are providing dense spectroscopic follow-up of SN II discoveries. The Rubin Observatory (LSST) will discover ~10
\f2 \uc0\u8308 
\f0  SN II per year starting in 2025, with a spectroscopic follow-up ecosystem (4MOST TiDES, DESI follow-up programs) to characterize the most useful subset.\

\f1\b Methodological refinements.
\f0\b0  The TARDIS code and competitor codes are being updated continuously; better atomic data, better treatment of time-dependent ionization, and better handling of mild asymmetry are all in active development.\

\f1\b Cross-validation with classical EPM and SCM.
\f0\b0  As samples grow, you can cross-validate tailored EPM against SCM in the same SNe and against classical EPM in archival samples. This provides ongoing systematic checks.\
The plausible state of the method by ~2028 is 
\f1\b ~1% precision per H
\f4 \uc0\u8320 
\f1  measurement
\f0\b0 , with ~50\'96100 SN II in the sample. This would be competitive with SH0ES on its own terms \'97 fully geometric, fully ladder-free, with completely orthogonal systematics.\
}